<section id="guide" class="panel active">
  <div class="hero-note"><strong>Built only from Professor PowerPoint Chapter 9, Parts 1 and 2.</strong><br>
  Use this page to review the lecture material in simple English.</div>
  <div class="grid"><section class="study-card"><h3>1. Standard Precautions</h3><ul><li>Used for every patient, even when no infection is known.</li><li>Apply to blood; body fluids, secretions, and excretions except sweat; nonintact skin; and mucous membranes.</li><li>Main goal: prevent HAIs and protect patients, staff, and the community.</li><li>Transmission-based precautions are the second tier and are used for specific infections.</li></ul></section><section class="study-card"><h3>2. Hand Hygiene and Gloves</h3><ul><li>Soap and water: 40–60 seconds.</li><li>Alcohol-based hand rub: 20–30 seconds when hands are not visibly dirty.</li><li>Clean hands before patient contact and aseptic tasks.</li><li>Clean hands after patient contact, glove removal, or touching nearby equipment.</li><li>Gloves are used for blood, body fluids, mucous membranes, and broken skin.</li><li>Change gloves between dirty and clean tasks—even on the same patient.</li><li>Natural, unpolished, short, neat fingernails.</li></ul></section><section class="study-card"><h3>3. PPE</h3><ul><li>Masks, eye protection, and face shields protect the eyes, nose, and mouth from splashes or sprays.</li><li>Do not touch the front of a used mask.</li><li>A surgical mask is not the same as an N95 respirator.</li><li>Use a clean, nonsterile gown for most procedures.</li><li>Choose gown material based on expected fluid exposure.</li></ul></section><section class="study-card"><h3>4. Needles, Tattooing, Equipment, and Linen</h3><ul><li>Wear gloves for tattooing.</li><li>Clean skin with alcohol and allow it to dry fully.</li><li>Never reuse an ink syringe.</li><li>Discard needles immediately in a sharps container at the point of use.</li><li>Never recap or manipulate a used needle.</li><li>Reprocess reusable equipment before reuse. Dispose of single-use items.</li><li>Treat contaminated linen as potentially infectious.</li></ul></section><section class="study-card"><h3>5. Respiratory Hygiene</h3><ul><li>Identify and isolate symptomatic patients or visitors.</li><li>Offer masks to coughing patients.</li><li>Provide tissues, no-touch trash cans, signage, and alcohol hand rub.</li><li>Use a private room or designated area when a person cannot follow cough etiquette.</li></ul></section><section class="study-card"><h3>6. HCW Rights, OSHA, and Confidentiality</h3><ul><li>HCWs may refuse unsafe work but must report the unsafe condition.</li><li>The employer must be informed before OSHA is contacted.</li><li>Retaliation for reporting is illegal.</li><li>Education should correct misinformation and fear.</li><li>After education shows minimal risk, refusal to care may result in termination.</li><li>Work-acquired infection must be proven for Workers’ Compensation.</li><li>HCW medical information and patient records must remain confidential.</li></ul></section><section class="study-card"><h3>7. Central Service and Reprocessing</h3><ul><li>CSD prepares, sterilizes, and distributes equipment.</li><li>Centralization improves efficiency, cost-effectiveness, and quality.</li><li>CSD must meet The Joint Commission standards.</li><li>Equipment is pre-cleaned, decontaminated, disassembled, processed, sterilized, and labeled with a control number.</li></ul></section><section class="study-card"><h3>8. Equipment Classification</h3><ul><li>Critical: must be sterile. Example: surgical instruments.</li><li>Semicritical: high-level disinfection is acceptable. Example: endoscopes.</li><li>Noncritical: contacts intact skin and is cleaned. Example: blood pressure cuffs.</li><li>Sterilization destroys all microbial life, including spores.</li><li>Disinfection lowers microbial load.</li><li>Antiseptics are used on skin.</li></ul></section><section class="study-card"><h3>9. Sterilization Methods</h3><ul><li>Steam/autoclave: steam under pressure; most common, reliable, and cost-effective.</li><li>Gravity displacement: about 121°C for 15–30 minutes.</li><li>Prevacuum: about 132°C for 4 minutes.</li><li>Dry heat: 150–170°C for 60–150 minutes; glassware, powders, metal tools.</li><li>Incineration: biohazard waste.</li><li>ETO gas: heat-sensitive equipment; slower and more costly.</li><li>Hydrogen peroxide plasma: fast, low residue, not for cellulose.</li><li>Ozone: low temperature; may be used for stainless steel.</li><li>Radiation: industrial gamma or X-ray sterilization; not routinely used in the facility.</li><li>Chemical liquids require careful selection, compatibility checks, and disposal.</li></ul></section><section class="study-card"><h3>10. Quality Control</h3><ul><li>Indicators: mechanical, chemical, and biologic.</li><li>Biologic indicators are the gold standard.</li><li>The Joint Commission requires routine testing and documentation.</li></ul></section></div>
</section>

<section id="must" class="panel">
  <div class="mustknow">
    <h2>⭐ Must Know Numbers</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Soap and water:</strong> 40–60 seconds</li>
      <li><strong>Alcohol hand rub:</strong> 20–30 seconds</li>
      <li><strong>Gravity steam:</strong> about 121°C for 15–30 minutes</li>
      <li><strong>Prevacuum steam:</strong> about 132°C for 4 minutes</li>
      <li><strong>Dry heat:</strong> 150–170°C for 60–150 minutes</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="grid">
    <section class="study-card"><h3>Hand Hygiene</h3><p>The most important and effective way to reduce HAIs.</p></section>
    <section class="study-card"><h3>Gloves</h3><p>Wear for blood, body fluids, mucous membranes, broken skin, and tattooing. Gloves never replace hand hygiene.</p></section>
    <section class="study-card"><h3>Needles</h3><p>Never recap. Never reuse ink syringes. Dispose immediately at the point of use.</p></section>
    <section class="study-card"><h3>Critical Items</h3><p>Must be sterile.</p></section>
    <section class="study-card"><h3>Sterilization</h3><p>Destroys all microbial life, including spores.</p></section>
    <section class="study-card"><h3>Gold Standard</h3><p>Biologic indicator.</p></section>
    <section class="study-card"><h3>OSHA</h3><p>Report the unsafe condition to the employer first. Retaliation is illegal.</p></section>
    <section class="study-card"><h3>Traceability</h3><p>Reprocessed equipment receives a control number.</p></section>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="terms" class="panel">
<table class="term-table">
<tr><td>HAI</td><td>Healthcare-associated infection.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Standard Precautions</td><td>Basic precautions used for every patient.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Transmission-Based Precautions</td><td>Extra precautions for a specific infection.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Aseptic</td><td>Preventing contamination by microorganisms.</td></tr>
<tr><td>CSD</td><td>Central Service Department.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Critical Item</td><td>An item that must be sterile.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Semicritical Item</td><td>An item that requires high-level disinfection.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Noncritical Item</td><td>An item that contacts intact skin and requires cleaning.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Sterilization</td><td>Destroys all microbial life, including spores.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Disinfection</td><td>Reduces microbial load.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Antiseptic</td><td>A chemical used on skin.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Autoclave</td><td>A device that sterilizes using steam under pressure.</td></tr>
<tr><td>ETO</td><td>Ethylene oxide gas used for heat-sensitive equipment.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Biologic Indicator</td><td>The gold-standard test of sterilization effectiveness.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Traceability</td><td>Ability to track a reprocessed item using its control number.</td></tr>
</table>
</section>

