iation is illegal."}, {"q": "After education proves the risk is minimal, continued refusal to care for a patient may result in:", "choices": ["Automatic promotion", "Termination", "A sterilization audit", "Workers’ Compensation"], "a": 1, "e": "The slide states refusal after education and minimal risk may lead to termination."}, {"q": "For Workers’ Compensation, an infection must be proven to be:", "choices": ["Community-acquired", "Work-acquired", "Genetic", "Present before employment"], "a": 1, "e": "It must be work-acquired and within the scope of practice."}, {"q": "Additional legal claims for a work infection generally require proof of:", "choices": ["A missed handwashing opportunity", "Intentional harm", "A patient complaint", "A positive culture only"], "a": 1, "e": "Additional claims are allowed only if intentional harm is proven."}, {"q": "Who should have access to a patient chart?", "choices": ["Any hospital employee", "Only staff directly involved in care", "All visitors", "Other patients"], "a": 1, "e": "Patient records are limited to those directly involved in care."}, {"q": "What is a major role of the Central Service Department?", "choices": ["Writing prescriptions", "Preparing, sterilizing, and distributing equipment", "Planning radiation dose", "Interpreting CT scans"], "a": 1, "e": "CSD manages equipment preparation, sterilization, and distribution."}, {"q": "Why is equipment reprocessing often centralized?", "choices": ["To eliminate documentation", "For efficiency and cost-effectiveness", "To avoid quality standards", "To allow reuse of all disposable items"], "a": 1, "e": "Centralization improves efficiency and cost-effectiveness."}, {"q": "Which organization’s quality standards apply to Central Service?", "choices": ["ARRT only", "The Joint Commission", "OSHA only", "FDA only"], "a": 1, "e": "The slide states CSD must meet TJC quality standards."}, {"q": "What is the first step for contaminated equipment?", "choices": ["Immediate packaging", "Pre-cleaning and decontamination", "Labeling as sterile", "Returning it to use"], "a": 1, "e": "Contaminated equipment is first pre-cleaned and decontaminated."}, {"q": "Why is a control number placed on reprocessed equipment?", "choices": ["To show its purchase price", "For traceability", "To identify the patient’s diagnosis", "To replace biologic testing"], "a": 1, "e": "The control number allows traceability."}, {"q": "A surgical instrument is classified as:", "choices": ["Critical", "Semicritical", "Noncritical", "Disposable only"], "a": 0, "e": "Critical items must be sterile."}, {"q": "An endoscope is classified as:", "choices": ["Critical in every situation", "Semicritical", "Noncritical", "Environmental equipment"], "a": 1, "e": "The slide gives endoscopes as semicritical items."}, {"q": "A blood pressure cuff is classified as:", "choices": ["Critical", "Semicritical", "Noncritical", "Sterile implant"], "a": 2, "e": "A BP cuff contacts intact skin and is noncritical."}, {"q": "Which process destroys all microbial life, including spores?", "choices": ["Cleaning", "Antisepsis", "Disinfection", "Sterilization"], "a": 3, "e": "Sterilization destroys all microbial life, including spores."}, {"q": "Antiseptics are used on:", "choices": ["Skin", "Treatment couches only", "Metal instruments only", "Biohazard waste"], "a": 0, "e": "Antiseptics are for skin, not inanimate objects."}, {"q": "What is the most common and reliable sterilization method?", "choices": ["Ozone", "Steam under pressure", "Dry wiping", "Ultraviolet room light"], "a": 1, "e": "Steam sterilization is the most common, cost-effective, and reliable."}, {"q": "Typical gravity-displacement steam sterilization uses:", "choices": ["121°C for about 15–30 minutes", "132°C for 4 minutes", "170°C for 10 minutes", "100°C for 2 hours"], "a": 0, "e": "Gravity displacement: about 121°C for 15–30 minutes."}, {"q": "Typical prevacuum steam sterilization uses:", "choices": ["121°C for 60 minutes", "132°C for 4 minutes", "150°C for 150 minutes", "170°C for 4 minutes"], "a": 1, "e": "Prevacuum: about 132°C for 4 minutes."}, {"q": "Which is a limitation of steam sterilization?", "choices": ["It cannot destroy microbes", "It may damage heat-sensitive items", "It leaves all spores alive", "It cannot be monitored"], "a": 1, "e": "Heat-sensitive items and corrosion are limitations."}, {"q": "Dry heat is best suited for:", "choices": ["Cellulose dressings", "Glassware, powders, and metal tools", "Living skin", "Plastic tubing only"], "a": 1, "e": "Dry heat is used for glassware, powders, and metal tools."}, {"q": "Incineration is mainly used for:", "choices": ["Skin antisepsis", "Biohazard waste", "Blood pressure cuffs", "Endoscopes"], "a": 1, "e": "Incineration is used for biohazard waste."}, {"q": "Which sterilant is used for heat-sensitive equipment such as endoscopes?", "choices": ["Ethylene oxide", "Soap and water", "Alcohol hand rub", "Steam only"], "a": 0, "e": "ETO is used for heat-sensitive equipment."}, {"q": "A disadvantage of ethylene oxide is that it is:", "choices": ["Too fast", "Slower and more costly", "Only for stainless steel", "Unable to sterilize"], "a": 1, "e": "ETO is slower and more costly."}, {"q": "Hydrogen peroxide plasma is NOT appropriate for:", "choices": ["Low-temperature processing", "Cellulose materials", "Fast processing", "Low-residue processing"], "a": 1, "e": "The slide states it is not for cellulose."}, {"q": "Radiation sterilization in this chapter is described as:", "choices": ["Routine in the treatment room", "Industrial use with gamma rays or X-rays", "A replacement for hand hygiene", "A method used on patient skin"], "a": 1, "e": "Radiation sterilization is industrial and not used routinely in the facility."}, {"q": "Which sterilization indicator is the gold standard?", "choices": ["Mechanical", "Chemical", "Biologic", "Visual inspection"], "a": 2, "e": "Biologic indicators are the gold standard."}, {"q": "What does TJC require for sterilization quality control?", "choices": ["Testing only after an outbreak", "Routine testing and documentation", "No records if equipment looks clean", "Only mechanical indicators"], "a": 1, "e": "Routine testing and documentation are required."}];
let cards=[...flashcards], cardIndex=0;
let quiz=[], qi=0, score=0, answered=false, wrong=[];

document.querySelectorAll('.tab').forEach(btn=>btn.addEventListener('click',()=>{
  document.querySelectorAll('.tab').forEach(b=>b.classList.remove('active'));
  document.querySelectorAll('.panel').forEach(p=>p.classList.remove('active'));
  btn.classList.add('active');
  document.getElementById(btn.dataset.tab).classList.add('active');
}));

const fc=document.getElementById('flashcard');
fc.addEventListener('click',()=>fc.classList.toggle('flipped'));
function renderCard(){
  fc.classList.remove('flipped');
  document.getElementById('fcQ').textContent=cards[cardIndex][0];
  document.getElementById('fcA').textContent=cards[cardIndex][1];
  document.getElementById('fcCount').textContent=`Card ${cardIndex+1} of ${cards.length}`;
  document.getElementById('fcProgress').style.width=((cardIndex+1)/cards.length*100)+'%';
}
function nextCard(){cardIndex=(cardIndex+1)%cards.length;renderCard();}
function prevCard(){cardIndex=(cardIndex-1+cards.length)%cards.length;renderCard();}
function shuffleCards(){cards.sort(()=>Math.random()-.5);cardIndex=0;renderCard();}

function shuffle(arr){return [...arr].sort(()=>Math.random()-.5)}
function startQuiz(){
  quiz=shuffle(quizBank).map(item=>{
    const tagged=item.choices.map((c,i)=>({text:c,correct:i===item.a}));
    return {q:item.q,e:item.e,choices:shuffle(tagged)};
  });
  qi=0;score=0;answered=false;wrong=[];renderQuestion();
}
function renderQuestion(){
  const area=document.getElementById('quizArea');
  if(qi>=quiz.length) return renderResults();
  const item=quiz[qi];
  area.innerHTML=`<div class="small">Question ${qi+1} of ${quiz.length} • Score: ${score}</div>
  <div class="progress"><span style="width:${qi/quiz.length*100}%"></span></div>
  <div class="quiz-card"><h2>${item.q}</h2>
  <div id="choices">${item.choices.map((c,i)=>`<button class="choice" onclick="choose(${i})">${String.fromCharCode(65+i)}. ${c.text}</button>`).join('')}</div>
  <div class="explain" id="explain"></div>
  <div class="controls"><button class="btn primary" id="nextQ" style="display:none" onclick="nextQuestion()">Next Question →</button></div></div>`;
}
function choose(index){
  if(answered)return; answered=true;
  const item=quiz[qi], buttons=[...document.querySelectorAll('.choice')];
  buttons.forEach((b,i)=>{
    if(item.choices[i].correct)b.classList.add('correct');
  });
  if(item.choices[index].correct)score++;
  else{buttons[index].classList.add('wrong');wrong.push(item.q)}
  const ex=document.getElementById('explain');
  ex.style.display='block';
  ex.innerHTML=`<strong>${item.choices[index].correct?'Correct!':'Not quite.'}</strong> ${item.e}`;
  document.getElementById('nextQ').style.display='inline-block';
}
function nextQuestion(){qi++;answered=false;renderQuestion();}
function renderResults(){
  const pct=Math.round(score/quiz.length*100);
  document.getElementById('quizArea').innerHTML=`<div class="scorebox">
  <h1>${pct}%</h1><h2>${score} / ${quiz.length} correct</h2>
  <p>${pct>=90?'Excellent work!':pct>=75?'Good job. Review the missed topics once more.':'Review the study guide and try again.'}</p>
  ${wrong.length?`<details><summary><strong>Questions to review (${wrong.length})</strong></summary><ul style="text-align:left">${wrong.map(x=>`<li>${x}</li>`).join('')}</ul></details>`:'<p>You did not miss any questions. 🎉</p>'}
  <button class="btn primary" onclick="startQuiz()">Restart and Shuffle</button></div>`;
}
renderCard(); startQuiz();
</script>
